{'text': 'As the number of COVID cases surged in India, Harvard Business School student Shyamli Badgaiyan quickly organized a fundraising effort that raised more than $160,000 in its first week.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Shyamli joined forces with Priyank Lathwal, a Ph.D. student at Carnegie Mellon, and together they mobilized South Asian student organizations from more than 20 universities across the country. Using a united platform to pool funds, the donations are channeled to the organizations working in India to alleviate shortages in oxygen, protective equipment, and other medical supplies that are straining the healthcare system. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs been incredibly heartening to see this collective action materialize, albeit heartbreaking to know just how needed our efforts have been,‚Äù said Shyamli.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Photo: @rosie_lincoln/Harvard Staff Photographer'}

{'text': "Jeremy Lin ‚Äô10 has been chosen by the undergraduate Class of 2021 to give this year's Class Day address. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
At Harvard, Lin spent four record-shattering years as a star point guard for the Crimson, and was team captain his senior year. After graduation, he went on to have a storied, nine-year pro career, becoming the first American-born player of Chinese or Taiwanese descent to play in the NBA. A philanthropist and an activist, Lin has stepped up to help those affected by the COVID-19 pandemic, and become an advocate in the fight against anti-Asian racism. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
‚ÄúJeremy Lin has been an inspirational figure for so many of us, and the example of his work and the ways he lives his values shine more brightly now than ever,‚Äù said Samyra Miller ‚Äô21, first marshal and co-chair of the speaker selection committee. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Harvard College's Class Day ceremony will be held virtually on May 26.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
#Harvard21 #Harvard‚†Ä
‚†Ä
Photo courtesy of Jeremy Lin"}

{'text': '#TBT May 6, 1981: Forty years ago today, officials visited the dormitory of a 21-year-old Yale senior Maya Lin ‚Äô81, MArch ‚Äô86, to inform her that she had won a national competition with 1,420 entries, to design the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, DC. 

Her now-iconic design, made up of two long black granite walls inscribed with the names of servicemen and women who gave their lives, was developed as a class project and inspired by the carvings in Yale‚Äôs Memorial Rotunda.

Yale Alumni Magazine [@yalealumnimag] reported on the achievement in its Summer 1981 issue, seen here.

#MayaLin #VietnamMemorial #YaleWomen #YaleAlumni #Yale'}
